DialInfo can contain a dial function as such:
{noformat}
Dial func(addr net.Addr) (net.Conn, error)
{noformat}

The Dial func is always called, by mgo, passing in an already DNS resolved net.TCPAddr. This means the implementing function can not create a TLS connection requiring host verification using the commonName/SANs from a certificate.

For example:
{noformat}
return func(addr net.Addr) (net.Conn, error) {
    return tls.Dial("tcp", addr.String(), &tls.Config{RootCAs: certs})
}
{noformat}

I have a cluster (2 replica sets, 3 config servers, 2 mongosses), created by
Automation.

I was trying to have Automation create a user "wizard@admin" using the usual
Go-driver command, UpsertUser. It failed, with the following message. The
"SyncClusterConnection::update upsert query needs _id" comes from Mongod. The
other stuff is from Automation and mgo.

{code}
<mongos2> Error calling UpsertUser on db=admin for user=&mgo.User{Username:"wizard", Password:"", PasswordHash:"703a9e87468e895372e0f2f23c5e15eb", UserSource:"", Roles:[]mgo.Role{}, OtherDBRoles:map[string][]mgo.Role{}} : SyncClusterConnection::update upsert query needs _id
{code}

The same code works for creating users in databases other than "admin".

I talked with Andy and Greg, who recommended that I run the mongods with
verbose=true, and the mongosses with vvv. Here are the whole log files.

9001-9003 are one replica set
9004-9006 are another
9007-9007 are the config servers 
9010 and 9989 are the mongosses.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Here's the source of the mgo driver command, in case that's any help.  I'll be
glad to interpret.  It's ultimately doing an upsert on admin.system.users.

{code}
func (db *Database) UpsertUser(user *User) error {
	if user.Username == "" {
		return fmt.Errorf("user has no Username")
	}
	if user.Password != "" {
		psum := md5.New()
		psum.Write([]byte(user.Username + ":mongo:" + user.Password))
		user.PasswordHash = hex.EncodeToString(psum.Sum(nil))
		user.Password = ""
	}
	if user.PasswordHash != "" && user.UserSource != "" {
		return fmt.Errorf("user has both Password/PasswordHash and UserSource set")
	}
	if len(user.OtherDBRoles) > 0 && db.Name != "admin" {
		return fmt.Errorf("user with OtherDBRoles is only supported in admin database")
	}
	var unset bson.D
	if user.PasswordHash == "" {
		unset = append(unset, bson.DocElem{"pwd", 1})
	}
	if user.UserSource == "" {
		unset = append(unset, bson.DocElem{"userSource", 1})
	}
	// user.Roles is always sent, as it's the way MongoDB distinguishes
	// old-style documents from new-style documents.
	if len(user.OtherDBRoles) == 0 {
		unset = append(unset, bson.DocElem{"otherDBRoles", 1})
	}
	c := db.C("system.users")
	_, err := c.Upsert(bson.D{{"user", user.Username}}, bson.D{{"$unset", unset}, {"$set", user}})
	return err
}
{code}
